  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "ML algorithms can generally be construed as 'Narrow AI'.",
    "The definition of ML we use is the classic definition from Mitchell (1997): \"A computer program is said to learn from experience E with respect to some class of tasks T and performance measure P, if its performance at tasks in T, as measured by P, improves with experience E.\".",
    "Several Machine Learning algorithms have been deployed in the service of AI polling, e.g., LASSO, k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Regression trees, Random Forests, Gradient Boosting Machines, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) (Bisbee 2019; Goplerud 2023; Ornstein 2019; Leemann et al. 2020; Cerina and Duch 2020), etc. AI polling is also, as we said, fuelled by Big Data 3.",
    "We follow Warshaw's characterisation of Big Data in the context of public opinion research (Warshaw 2016) to describe the use of large surveys, such as the Cooperative Congressional Election Study, the National Annenberg Election Survey, the very large set of Xbox gamers in Wang et al.",
    "(Wang et al. 2015), as well as others."
  ],
